First, the assay names were examined.

assayNames(gse)
## [1] "counts"    "abundance" "length"

Counts are the estimated fragment counts for each gene and sample. Abundance is the estimated transcript abundanes in TPM. Length is the the effective gene lengths including changes in length due to biases as well as to transcript usage.

The donor cell line column was renamed to cell.

gse$cell <- gse$donor

The treatment condition column was renamed to dex.

gse$dex <- gse$condition

The levels of the dex column were renamed to an abbreviated version. Untreated was changed to untrt and Dexamethasone was changed to trt. It is important to maintain the original order of the levels.

levels(gse$dex)
## [1] "Untreated"     "Dexamethasone"
levels(gse$dex) <- c("untrt", "trt")

It is preferred that the first level is the reference/control level, in this case untreated or untrt. The data was releveled and untrt was set as the reference.

library("magrittr")
gse$dex %<>% relevel("untrt")
gse$dex
## [1] untrt trt   untrt trt   untrt trt   untrt trt  
## Levels: untrt trt

In the magrittr package, %<>% is a concise way of saying gse\(dex <- relevel(gse\)dex, untrt).

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) > 1
dds <- dds[keep,]

The new number of rows.

nrow(dds)

An additional filter was added that at least three of the samples have a count of 10 or higher.

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds) >= 10) >= 3

A plot was created depicting the standard deviation of each row (gene) against the mean. This plot shows that variance increases when the mean increases. The low counts may be making too much noise.

lambda <- 10^seq(from = -1, to = 2, length = 1000)
cts <- matrix(rpois(1000*100, lambda), ncol = 100)
library("vsn")
meanSdPlot(cts, ranks = FALSE)

This plot depicts the same information but with the log of each variable. This prevents the plot from depending on the rows with the highest counts which have higher differences.

log.cts.one <- log2(cts + 1)
meanSdPlot(log.cts.one, ranks = FALSE)

The variance stabilizing transformation (vst) function can be used for negative binomial data with a dispersion-mean trend. It is faster and less sensitive to outliers.

vsd <- vst(dds, blind = FALSE)

The heat map package was loaded.

library("pheatmap")
library("RColorBrewer")

A heat map was created to visualize the distances between samples. sampleDists was manually provided to the clustering_distance augment of the function so that the data from the matrix itself was not used, instead the data from the dist function.

sampleDistMatrix <- as.matrix( sampleDists )
rownames(sampleDistMatrix) <- paste( vsd$dex, vsd$cell, sep = " - " )
colnames(sampleDistMatrix) <- NULL
colors <- colorRampPalette( rev(brewer.pal(9, "Blues")) )(255)
pheatmap(sampleDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows = sampleDists,
         clustering_distance_cols = sampleDists,
         col = colors)

The Possion distance methods measures the dissimilarity between counts while taking into consideration the inherent variance structure of counts when calculating the distances between samples. First, the counts in dds must be transposed because the Poisson Distance method takes the unnormalized count matrix with the samples as rows instead of columns.

library("PoiClaClu")
poisd <- PoissonDistance(t(counts(dds)))

A heat map is created using the Poisson Distance method.

samplePoisDistMatrix <- as.matrix( poisd$dd )
rownames(samplePoisDistMatrix) <- paste( dds$dex, dds$cell, sep=" - " )
colnames(samplePoisDistMatrix) <- NULL
pheatmap(samplePoisDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows = poisd$dd,
         clustering_distance_cols = poisd$dd,
         col = colors)

A principal components analysis (PCA) is another way of plotting distances between samples. The x-axis (PC1) represents the direction that separates the data points the most. The y-axis (PC2) is the direction that separates the data the second most (must be orthogonal to the first).

plotPCA(vsd, intgroup = c("dex", "cell"))

The data from the PCA plot.

pcaData <- plotPCA(vsd, intgroup = c( "dex", "cell"), returnData = TRUE)

  coord_fixed() +
  ggtitle("PCA with VST data")

The eneralized principal component analysis (glmpca) package is also used for dimension reduction on data that is not Normally distributed. The package takes the count matrix as input, as well as the number of latent dimensions to fit (in this example, 2).

library("glmpca")
gpca <- glmpca(counts(dds), L=2)
gpca.dat <- gpca$factors
gpca.dat$dex <- dds$dex
gpca.dat$cell <- dds$cell
ggplot(gpca.dat, aes(x = dim1, y = dim2, color = dex, shape = cell)) +
  geom_point(size =3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("glmpca - Generalized PCA")

The multidimensional scaling function (mds) is useful when there is no matrix of data, but ONLY a matrix of distances. The plot below represents the mds for the distances calculated from the vst data.

mds <- as.data.frame(colData(vsd))  %>%
  cbind(cmdscale(sampleDistMatrix))
ggplot(mds, aes(x = `1`, y = `2`, color = dex, shape = cell)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("MDS with VST data")

This plot is the mds for the Poisson Distance data.

mdsPois <- as.data.frame(colData(dds)) %>%
  cbind(cmdscale(samplePoisDistMatrix))
ggplot(mdsPois, aes(x = `1`, y = `2`, color = dex, shape = cell)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("MDS with PoissonDistances")
